abstract = {Variable combinations of factors (such as: competition, fuel costs, improving heat rates for new generation units, age, more stringent environmental regulations, or sociological issues) have led a number of industrial facilities and sites to obsolescence. The reader should note that most of these factors—and others discussed in this chapter—apply to nuclear power plants as well as fossil-fired units. There are also many nonpower plants and individual structures that became redundant and were subject to different forms of redevelopment, ranging from mere preservation with a minimum renovation to more drastic changes. At heritage sites, developers strive to preserve the identity and character of the former uses. The economics and stakeholders' interests in industrial reuse and heritage, when supported by adequate location and architectural dimensions, have created many opportunities for adaptive reuse. A wide range of case histories—categorized according to prior use and as redeveloped—are illustrated in this chapter.}
